# SwiftUI: avoid `@ObservedObject`

- **Do not** declare `@ObservedObject` on views in this project. It couples views to `ObservableObject`, obscures ownership, and fights the **`@Observable`** + **`Observation`** pattern used elsewhere.

## What to use instead

- **Parent-created / injected model** — take **`@Bindable var model: SomeModel`** (or plain `let model` when the view only reads) where `SomeModel` is **`@Observable`**.
- **View-owned model** — use **`@State private var model = SomeModel()`** for `@Observable` types.
- If you must interoperate with legacy **`ObservableObject`** types temporarily, prefer **`@StateObject`** only where the view **owns** the object, or lift the instance to **`@Observable`** and pass **`@Bindable`** — do not add new `@ObservedObject` usage.

```swift
// ❌ BAD
struct GameView: View {
    @ObservedObject var viewModel: GameViewModel
    var body: some View { /* ... */ }
}

// ✅ GOOD — @Observable view model + @Bindable
struct GameView: View {
    @Bindable var viewModel: GameViewModel
    var body: some View { /* ... */ }
}

// ✅ GOOD — view owns the model
struct GameView: View {
    @State private var viewModel = GameViewModel()
    var body: some View { /* ... */ }
}
```
